<Group labelreference="L54" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Title" layout="Title"><Font underline="true">Computer Assignmet 1</Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[255,204,153]">Question 1) </Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">How could you modify the procedure LargestComponent from the end of section 1.2 to return
the position of the largest component within the vector v, as opposed to the component with
the largest absolute value?</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">Original Code:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L58" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">LargestComponent := proc(v::Vector)
local k, i;
k := abs(v[1]);
for i from 1 to Dimension(v) do
if k &lt; abs(v[i]) then k := abs(v[i]) end if
end do;
return k;
end proc</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L65" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">An example of this Code in use is:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L64" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">LargestComponent(Vector([3,1,4,1,5,9,2,6,5]))</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display="LUkjbW5HNiMvSSttb2R1bGVuYW1lRzYiSSxUeXBlc2V0dGluZ0dJKF9zeXNsaWJHRic2JFEiOUYnLyUsbWF0aHZhcmlhbnRHUSdub3JtYWxGJw==">IiIq</Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L68" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">This returns the largest component of any vector input.</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">In order to change the code to give the position of the largest component, we need to alter the code (and the name for convinience). </Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">Any changes are highlighted in yellow:</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L69" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[255,255,0]">LargestComponentPositionfunction</Font>:=proc(v::Vector)
local k,i<Font opaque="true" background="[255,255,0]">,Position</Font>;
k:=abs(v[1]);
for i from 1 to Dimension(v) do
if k &lt; abs(v[i]) then k := abs(v[i]); <Font opaque="true" background="[255,255,0]">Position:=i</Font> end if
end do;
return <Font opaque="true" background="[255,255,0]">Position</Font>;
end proc</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L73" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">We have introduced a new variable called &quot;Position&quot; that will take the value of  &quot;i&quot; when the code finds the highest value, when k &lt; abs(v[i]) is satisfied. </Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">We can test this using the same test-vector as before: The largest value is 9 and so our new code should return the position of 9 in the vector.</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L70" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">LargestComponentPosition(Vector([3,1,4,1,5,<Font opaque="true" background="[204,153,255]">9</Font>,2,6,5]))</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L72" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">The sixth value of our test-vector [3,1,4,1,5,<Font opaque="true" background="[204,153,255]">9</Font>,2,6,5] is indeed 9 and the largest! Hence, the code works. </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L74" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[255,204,153]">Question 2) Let A be the matrix</Font></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L85" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">A:=Matrix([[-1,-1,2,0],[1,1,-1,0],[0,0,-1,1],[1,0,0,-1]]);</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L79" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]">i) Use Maple to find the characteristic polynomial of A.</Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">To do this, all we need to do is use the <Font bold="true">characteristic polynomial funtion!</Font> Given by:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L80" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">CharacteristicPolynomialFunction:=proc(M::Matrix)
local d,J,C;
d:=RowDimension(M);
J:=IdentityMatrix(d);
C:=Determinant(a*J-M);
return C;
end proc
</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L87" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">What the <Font bold="true">Characteristic Polynomial Function</Font> does is first take the row dimension of our matrix (it can be either row or column dimension as only square matrices produce the required determinant) and saves it's value as &quot;d&quot;. We then form an identity matrix &quot;J&quot; of dimension &quot;d&quot; so that it has the same dimensions as our input matrix. Lastly, we return the determinant of (a*J-M) which forms our characteristic polynomal.</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">Let's try it below:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L82" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">CharacteristicPolynomialFunction(A)</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display="">LCwqJClJImFHNiIiIiUiIiJGKComIiIjRigpRiUiIiRGKEYoKiQpRiVGKkYoRigqJkYqRihGJUYoISIiRihGKA==</Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L88" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">This is the correct Characteristic Polynomial. </Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" bold="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" bold="false">ii) Use Mapleto verify that the matrix A satisfies the Cayley-Hamilton Theorem.</Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" bold="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">To do this, all we need to do is use the SatisfyTheCayleyHamiltonTheoremFunction</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L89" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">SatisfyTheCayleyHamiltonTheoremFunction:=proc(M::Matrix)
local d,J,Z,CTTCheck,i,j;
d:=RowDimension(M);
J:=IdentityMatrix(d);
Z:=ZeroMatrix(d);
CTTCheck:=simplify(subs(b=J,subs(a=M,b*CharacteristicPolynomialFunction(M))));
for i from 1 to d do
for j from 1 to d do
if CTTCheck[i,j]=Z[i,j] then return true else return false end if
end do
end do
end proc</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L100" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" bulletsuffix="."></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" bulletsuffix=".">What the <Font bold="true">Satisfy The Cayley-Hamilton Theorem Function</Font> does is:</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" bulletsuffix="."></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L101" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Finds the dimension of a matrix M and labels it &quot;d&quot;.</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Forms the identity and Zero matrix of equivalent dimension labelled &quot;J&quot; and &quot;Z&quot; respectively.</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Substitutes a Matrix M into it's Characteristic Polynomial (it multiplies the characteristic polynomial with the identity in order to deal with any constant values)</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">Now it verifies that the substitution is equivalent to the zero matrix of equal dimension.</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal" initial="-1" bulletsuffix="." bullet="numeric">If they are equal, the function returns with &quot;true&quot;, and if not then it returns with &quot;false&quot;.</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L102" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">Now we input our matrix into the <Font bold="true">Satisfy The Cayley-Hamilton Theorem Function</Font> and it should return true if the above holds. </Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L90" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">SatisfyTheCayleyHamiltonTheoremFunction(A)</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display="LUkjbWlHNiMvSSttb2R1bGVuYW1lRzYiSSxUeXBlc2V0dGluZ0dJKF9zeXNsaWJHRic2JVEldHJ1ZUYnLyUnaXRhbGljR0YrLyUsbWF0aHZhcmlhbnRHUSdpdGFsaWNGJw==">SSV0cnVlRyUqcHJvdGVjdGVkRw==</Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L104" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">As you can see the Matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> does satisfy the Cayley-Hamilton Theorem. </Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]">iii) Assuming that <Font bold="true">A</Font> is invertible, find the inverse of <Font bold="true">A</Font> using the Cayley-Hamilton Theorem. (Hint: rewrite the equation and multiply it by <Font bold="true">A</Font>^-1), doing the final calculation in Maple.</Font><Font opaque="true" background="[255,255,255]"> </Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[255,255,255]">Firstly, we need to work out the inverse using the Cayley-Hamilton Theorem:</Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal" alignment="centred"><Equation executable="true" style="2D Math" input-equation="" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L109" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">Ignore the above output. The working out is non-executable mathematics. 
Now we can produce an inverse using Maple:</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L110" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">ProduceTheInverseFunction:=proc(M::Matrix)
local J,d,N;
d:=RowDimension(M);
J:=IdentityMatrix(d);
N:=2*J-A-2*A^2-A^3;
return N
end proc</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L114" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">The Produce The Inverse Function substitutes the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> into our inverse function that we formed using the Cayley-Hamilton Theorem. This function only works for the unique matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font>. Now inputting <Font bold="true">A</Font> we get:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L111" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">ProduceTheInverseFunction(A)</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L113" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">Which is the correct inverse of the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font>.</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]">iv) Use Maple to verify that you have indeed found the matrix of <Font bold="true">A</Font>.</Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">To do this, we can first find the inverse in Maple Directly:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L115" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">A^(-1)</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L117" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">Which is equivalent to our solution. </Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">
<Font opaque="true" background="[0,255,0]">v) Use Maple to augment the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> by a suitable identity matrix and use Gauss-Jordan elimination to again find the inverse of <Font bold="true">A</Font>.</Font> </Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">To do this is to use the <Font bold="true">Gauss-Jordan Elimination Function</Font> seen below:</Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L123" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">GaussJordanEliminationFunction:=proc(M::Matrix)
local d1,d2,J;
d1:=RowDimension(M);
d2:=ColumnDimension(M);
J:=IdentityMatrix(d1);
if d1=d2 then return ReducedRowEchelonForm(&lt;M|J&gt;) else printf(&quot;Error: Must use Square Matrix!&quot;) end if
end proc</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L129" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">What this function does is determine the row and column dimension of a given matrix M and labels their values with d1 and d2 respectively. Then it forms an identity matrix of equal dimension. Then the function checks whether d1=d2, the row and column dimensions are equal. If they are not equal it will return an error message. If they are equal then the function augments the matrix with the identity matrix of equal dimension and then reduces the augmented matrix to row echelon form. </Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L124" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">GaussJordanEliminationFunction(A)</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L131" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[255,204,153]" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[255,204,153]">Question 3) Write a Maple procedure RowOperation1(A,p,q) which should take as input any matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> (of arbitrary size m cross n) and two integers p and q, and return the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> with the pth and qth rows swapped. </Font></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" opaque="true" background="[255,204,153]" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L132" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">RowOperation1:=proc(A::Matrix,p,q)::Matrix;
local d1,d2,Rp,Rq;
d1:=RowDimension(A);
d2:=ColumnDimension(A);
if (p&lt;=0 or q&lt;=0) then printf(&quot;Error: Please choose values of p and q that are non-negative&quot;);
elif (p&gt;d1 or q &gt; d1) then printf(&quot;Error: Please choose values of p and q that do not exceed the row dimensions of the matrix.&quot;) else Rp:=A[p,1..d2];Rq:=A[q,1..d2];
A[q,1..d2]:=Rp; A[p,1..d2]:=Rq;
return A;
end if;
end proc</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L136" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal">The Above function first defines the row and column dimension and labels them d1 and d2 respectively. If the value of p or q exceed the row dimension then the function returns an error message. If p and q do not exceed the row dimension then the function defines the pth and qth row as Rp and Rq respectively. Then it redefines the matrix's pth row as Rq and qth row as Rp. Then it returns the matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> with row operation. </Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L137" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">RowOperation1(A,1,3)</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group labelreference="L139" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"><Font opaque="true" background="[255,204,153]">Question 4) Write a Maple procedure RowOperation2(A,p,q,x) which should take as input any matrix <Font bold="true">A</Font> (of arbitrary size m cross n) and return the resilt of subtracting x times the qth row from the pth row if p neq q. However, if p=q then it should return the result of scaling the pth row by x.</Font> </Text-field><Text-field style="Text" layout="Normal"></Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L143" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">A:=Matrix([[-1,-1,2,0],[1,1,-1,0],[0,0,-1,1],[1,0,0,-1]])</Text-field>
</Input>
<Output><Text-field style="2D Output" layout="Maple Output"><Equation executable="false" style="2D Output" display=""></Equation></Text-field>
</Output>
</Group>
<Group hide-input="false" labelreference="L140" drawlabel="true" applyint="true" applyrational="true" applyexponent="false">
<Input><Text-field prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input" layout="Normal">RowOperation2:=proc(A::Matrix,p,q,x)::Matrix;
local d1,d2,Rp,Rq;
d1:=RowDimension(A);
d2:=ColumnDimension(A);
if (p&lt;=0 or q&lt;=0) then printf(&quot;Error: Please choose values of p and q that are non-negative&quot;);
elif (p&gt;d1 or q &gt; d1) then printf(&quot;Error: Please choose values of p and q that do not exceed the row dimensions of the matrix.&quot;);
elif p=q then Rp:=A[p,1..d2];A[p,1..d2]:=Rp/x;
else Rp:=A[p,1..d2];Rq:=A[q,1..d2];A[p,1..d2]:=Rp-x*Rq;
return A;
end if;
end proc:</Text-field>
</Input>
</Group>
